                    <item>
              <title>Tools for supervising student discussion</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/236</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/236</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[What tools does a teacher need for supervising, moderating or facilitating a student discussion?

George Kahrimanis and Nikolaos Avouris suggest several important features: (1) the ability to supervise easily multiple groups which may be collaborating synchronously; (2) metrics or indicators for the rate or level of participation and collaboration amongst students; (3) evident links between dialogue messages and actions in the shared workspace; (4) the ability to review student actions that have contributed to the group’s final solution.

See pp. 109-110, ‘Providing tools that aid the teachers who are supervising or participating in a NSCL activity’. TELL Pattern Book
]]></description>
