                    <item>
              <title>Designing or choosing collaborative tools</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/235</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/235</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[George Kahrimanis and Nikolaos Avouris have identified three issues to consider when designing or choosing a tool for collaborative working.

(1)  Should participants be able to have access to the shared workspace simultaneously, or should there be some kind of lock to ensure that only one person is making modifications at a time?

(2)  Should anyone be able to modify any material in the workspace, or should each participant retain ownership of the artefacts they originate, requiring others to get their consent for modification?

(3)  Is it more important to enable intense communication amongst a small group of participants or to support the knowledge-building of a large community?

For their discussion, follow the link and see pp. 106-107, ‘Choosing the optimal means of coordination of participants actions on a shared workspace’; p. 108, ‘Deciding on the rights of participants on object manipulation’; pp. 111-112, ‘Deciding on the nature of NSCL communication’. TELL Pattern Book
]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 17 Jun 2008 11:03:03 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Free chatting or structured dialogue?</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/234</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/234</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[Student discussion can be designed to be more or less structured, according to the choice of tool and the expectations and instructions set by the facilitator. When is free chatting best, and when is it appropriate to impose some form of structure?

George Kahrimanis and Nikolaos Avouris suggest that free chat is most appropriate where brainstorming or divergent thinking is required – for example, in the early stages of a problem solving activity, when students are agreeing strategy and dividing up tasks.

Structured dialogue, such as a requirement to define a category for each message or to use standard sentence openers or forms of argumentation, may be preferable where students need the help of such scaffolding to negotiate conflicting statements or make specific kinds of contributions to the task.

See pp. 104-105, ‘Choosing the appropriate means of dialogue in a NSCL tool for synchronous collaborative learning activities’ TELL Pattern Book
]]></description>
